  "position": "analytical_approach",
  "main_argument": "This is a classic application of Bayes' Theorem. We need to find P(drunk|positive test).",
  "key_points": [
    {
      "point": "Given information",
      "details": "False positive rate: 5% (breathalyzer shows drunk when sober), True positive rate: 100% (always detects drunk drivers), Base rate: 0.1% (1 in 1000 drivers are drunk)"
    },
    {
      "point": "Setup using Bayes' Theorem",
      "details": "P(drunk|positive) = P(positive|drunk) × P(drunk) / P(positive)"
    },
    {
      "point": "Calculate P(positive)",
      "details": "P(positive) = P(positive|drunk) × P(drunk) + P(positive|sober) × P(sober) = 1.0 × 0.001 + 0.05 × 0.999 = 0.001 + 0.04995 = 0.05095"
    },
    {
      "point": "Final calculation",
      "details": "P(drunk|positive) = (1.0 × 0.001) / 0.05095 = 0.001 / 0.05095 ≈ 0.0196 or about 1.96%"
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "Despite the positive breathalyzer test, the probability that the driver is actually drunk is only approximately 2%. This counterintuitive result occurs because the base rate of drunk drivers is so low (0.1%) that false positives from the much larger population of sober drivers (99.9%) dominate the positive test results.",
  "invitation_for_discussion": "I'm interested to hear if you approach this problem differently or if you'd like to discuss why this result seems counterintuitive to many people."
}

